06512nam a22012495i 9780691200880DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019954572  a97806912008807 a10.1515/97806912008802doi  a(DE-B1597)539905  a(OCoLC)1138025383  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHM716b.B45 2020 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a302.3/52231 aBell, Daniel A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJust Hierarchy :bWhy Social Hierarchies Matter in China and the Rest of the World /cDaniel A. Bell, Wang Pei. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b2 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Just Hierarchy between Intimates: On the Importance of Shifting Roles -- t2. Just Hierarchy between Citizens: On the Importance of Service -- t3. Just Hierarchy between States: On the Need for Reciprocity -- t4. Just Hierarchy between Humans and Animals: Subordination without Cruelty -- t5. Just Hierarchy between Humans and Machines: On the Need for a Master-Slave Relation -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA trenchant defense of hierarchy in different spheres of our lives, from the personal to the politicalAll complex and large-scale societies are organized along certain hierarchies, but the concept of hierarchy has become almost taboo in the modern world. Just Hierarchy contends that this stigma is a mistake. In fact, as Daniel Bell and Wang Pei show, it is neither possible nor advisable to do away with social hierarchies. Drawing their arguments from Chinese thought and culture as well as other philosophies and traditions, Bell and Wang ask which forms of hierarchy are justified and how these can serve morally desirable goals. They look at ways of promoting just forms of hierarchy while minimizing the influence of unjust ones, such as those based on race, sex, or caste.Which hierarchical relations are morally justified and why? Bell and Wang argue that it depends on the nature of the social relation and context. Different hierarchical principles ought to govern different kinds of social relations: what justifies hierarchy among intimates is different than what justifies hierarchy among citizens, countries, humans and animals, and humans and intelligent machines. Morally justified hierarchies can and should govern different spheres of our social lives, though these will be very different than the unjust hierarchies that have governed us in the past.A vigorous, systematic defense of hierarchy in the modern world, Just Hierarchy examines how hierarchical social relations can have a useful purpose, not only in personal domains but also in larger political realms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aHierarchieszChina. 0aHierarchies. 0aSocial groupszChina. 0aSocial groups. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAgainst Political Equality: The Confucian Case.  aAncient Chinese Thought, Modern Chinese Power.  aCommunist.  aConfucian Perfectionism: A Political Philosophy for Modern Times.  aJoseph Chan.  aMarx.  aPolitical thought.  aPrinceton-China Series.  aSilicon Valley.  aTongdong Bai.  aYan Xuetong.  aancient China.  aancient India.  aartificial intelligence.  acommunism.  acompetitive elections.  acontext.  ademocracy.  adomesticated.  aeating animals.  aegalitarianism.  aequal.  aequality.  aethics.  aexploit.  aexploitation.  afamily members.  afriends.  aglobal order.  ahousekeepers.  ahumane.  aliberal.  alovers.  ameritocracy.  apower.